{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655561"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:05:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:05:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18677"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18677","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18677"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11409"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76799"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11409"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18677"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62299"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10327"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26427"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26433"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76799"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMechanoreceptors in the skin are specialised to detect different types of touch sensations. These receptors vary in their adaptation rates and the specific stimuli they detect.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the function of Meissner corpuscles?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Monitor joint position","Detect temperature changes","Respond to stretching of hairy skin","Detect light touch and vibration in glabrous skin","Sense sustained pressure and texture"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct answer is that Meissner corpuscles \u003Cstrong\u003Edetect light touch and vibration in glabrous skin\u003C/strong\u003E. These rapidly adapting mechanoreceptors are located in the dermal papillae of glabrous (hairless) skin, particularly in the fingertips, palms, and soles. They are especially sensitive to dynamic changes in touch sensation and low-frequency vibration (20-50 Hz).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERespond to stretching of hairy skin\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of hair follicle receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESense sustained pressure and texture\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of Merkel cells, which are slowly adapting receptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDetect temperature changes\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of thermoreceptors\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMonitor joint position\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of proprioceptors like muscle spindles and Golgi tendon organs\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeissner corpuscles work alongside other mechanoreceptors like Pacinian corpuscles (which detect high-frequency vibration) and Merkel cells to provide detailed tactile information about objects we touch.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Meissner corpuscles are rapidly adapting mechanoreceptors that detect light touch and vibration in glabrous skin.","Pacinian corpuscles respond to rapid pressure changes and high-frequency vibration.","Merkel cells are slowly adapting mechanoreceptors that provide detailed information about sustained touch and pressure."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62299"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18677"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62299"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T13:09:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T13:10:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11409"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76799"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-27T10:23:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"13"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"ite